## tool_db_query: db_query tool definition

### db_query(sql: str) → str
Execute a SQL DML statement (SELECT / INSERT / UPDATE / DELETE) and receive the formatted result.

DDL is blocked: CREATE TABLE, DROP TABLE, ALTER TABLE, TRUNCATE, and RENAME are rejected by the tool. Use migrations or the admin interface for schema changes — never attempt DDL via db_query.

Active memory tables (samaritan_*):
- `samaritan_memory_shortterm` — hot facts auto-injected each session
- `samaritan_memory_longterm` — aged-out facts, query on demand
- `samaritan_chat_summaries` — session summaries written on !reset

When to use:
- Read or write memory facts → SELECT/INSERT/UPDATE on samaritan_memory_shortterm
- Inspect schema → SHOW TABLES, DESCRIBE <table>
- Any other DML task as directed by the reasoning layer

Table name rules:
- The `samaritan_*` tables above are the memory system tables.
- For all other tables, use the name as given. If a `samaritan_<name>` query fails with table-not-found, the system will automatically retry with the plain `<name>` — no manual retry needed.

CRITICAL: Always invoke db_query as a structured tool call. Never write raw SQL in your reply text.
